>I don't think 1089 has been appealed by three Players yet.  If it were
>to be appealed, then I would be on the Appelate Court for it, though I
>am not a Justice for CFJ 1090's appeal (because I judged it).
>
>So, whatever the merits of the current rules wrt this situation, they
>will not save us from having different Appeal Board Justices (if 1089
>is appealed).

The Appeal Board for the Appeal of CFJ 1090 is Morendil, Swann and myself.
Given that I appealed CFJ 1089 yesterday, what will be the makeup of the
Appeal Board for that Appeal? Presumably Morendil will be on it as
Justiciar, and you will be on it as CotC. What about me? This turns
out to be a surprisingly subtle question! 

Let's be a bit careful here for a moment and pay attention to details.
The new Speaker Transition Rules mean that I don't stop being Speaker
until you announce it (as Registrar). You are required to post a 
Notice of Speaker Transition "as soon as possible after the Speaker
Transition commences" (R402). When was that? According to R1581,
a Speaker Transition occurs "upon the commencement of each new
Quarter". Presumably, then, you incurred the obligation to post a
Notice of Speaker Transition as soon as possible after midnight GMT,
April 1. But wait! April 1, or April Fool's Day, was a Holiday, and
R1769 says that:

      If some Rule bases the time of a future event upon the time of
      another event, or requires that a Player perform some action
      within some time of another event, and that event occurs during
      a Holiday, the time at which the Holiday ends shall be used
      instead for the purpose of determining the time of the future
      event or of the time by which the Player must perform the
      specified action.

So the first question to be answered is: did the process of Speaker
Transition commence during the Holiday or just before it? If it was
during the Holiday, then the timing provisions of R1769 will be
operative. If not, the ordinary provisions of R1023 be effective. I
tend to think it must have been during the Holiday, because R1581
says that the Transition occurs "upon the commencement of each new
Quarter". If it had said "at the end of each Quarter", I would have
been inclined to hold that the Transition occurred before the Holiday
commenced, but it says "upon the commencement of each Quarter" so I
think we should rule that R1769 governs. If that's right, you didn't
incur the obligation to post a Notice of Speaker Transition until
the Holiday ended at midnight GMT, April _2_.

Now, what about the Appeal of CFJ 1089? I think I posted it about
0115 GMT, April 1. At any rate, it was definitely during the Holiday.
In the ordinary course of events, R1570 would require you (as CotC
this time) to post the announcement of Appeal as soon as possible
after the Appeal had been initiated. Becuase of the Holiday, however,
you did not in fact incur this obligation until the end of the
Holiday, once again, midnight GMT, April 2.

So, because of the Holiday, two separate obligations which you
would have incurred at different times you in fact incurred at
the same time. Note, however, that the question of which order you
incurred the obligations in is separate from the question of which
order you would have been required (sans Holiday), to perform them
in - because the requirements are due to separate Offices! *If* the
requirements had been associated with a single Office, and *if* they
had been imposed upon in a particular order, then R1023 would have
required you to perform them in that order. Remarkably, in the
present case, neither condition holds. Therefore, you are doubly
free to perform the actions required of you (announcing the Appeal
and posting the Notice of Speaker Transition) in whichever order
you prefer.

OK, so the next question is: does the order matter? Well, maybe.
Pretty clearly, if you choose to post the announcement of Appeal
before the Notice of Speaker Transition, then I'll still be 
Speaker and presumably serve on the Appeal Board. (Unless, of
course, some bright spark wants to argue that serving on the
Appeals Board is a "special right [or] privilege" of the Speaker
within the meaning of R402. But I doubt that that is true.)
If you chose that order, then 2 of the 3 Justices serving on the
Appeals would be the same.

If you choose the other order, what then? Here we're back in a
situation the Courts had to deal with a little while back, in
which the holder of the one of Justice-positions changes between
the time the Appeal is initiated and the time it is announced.
But I can't remember which we precedent we chose to set on that
previous occasion. I'll have to have a trawl through the Court
records.

Anyway, there it all is, laid out in its intricate detail. It's
all in your hands, really.

